│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                             │
│ My previous attempts to fix the crash have failed because they were too general and caused regressions in other tests. The original crash was on RISC-V, but my     │
│ changes broke an x86 test. This strongly suggests that the fix should be more targeted.                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ My last attempt, which checked if the `trunc` feeds an induction variable PHI, was still too broad. The core issue is that making the `trunc` free alters the cost  │
│ model in a way that leads to different, and in some cases incorrect, vectorization decisions.                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ I will try a new approach that is much more specific to the original failing test case. The reproducer has a `trunc` from `i64` to `i32`. The induction variable    │
│ `%iv` is `i64`, and the auxiliary induction variable `%iv.conv` is `i32`. The `trunc` connects these two.                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ My new hypothesis is that this `trunc` should only be considered free if it's a `trunc` from the pointer-sized integer type. On RISC-V 64-bit (as in the            │
│ reproducer), `i64` is the pointer size. The `trunc` is from `i64` to `i32`. This is a common pattern when dealing with array indices that might have been widened   │
│ to the full pointer width.                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ I will implement a patch that checks if the `trunc` instruction is truncating from the pointer integer type for the target. This is a much more constrained         │
│ heuristic than my previous attempts and is less likely to affect unrelated tests. The `LoopVectorizationCostModel` has access to the `DataLayout` via the           │
│ `TheFunction`, which can be used to get the pointer-sized integer type.                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ First, I will revert my previous change.                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                             │
│ sed -i '6348,6356d' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                                                                                 │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                 │
